WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.920
Today I would like to talk about the transition from RStudio to Positron and the ways in which

00:00:11.920 --> 00:00:18.400
you can make it less painful and more productive. This talk is particularly for you if you are

00:00:18.400 --> 00:00:23.719
curious about Positron or maybe you are already using it, but you still feel that RStudio

00:00:23.719 --> 00:00:29.719
is the place where you feel most comfortable. The situation that led to this talk is that

00:00:29.719 --> 00:00:36.799
I've been using RStudio for a long time, pretty much exclusively, and I love it. But

00:00:36.799 --> 00:00:43.599
I've also heard great things about Positron, so I got curious, I wanted to try. One of

00:00:43.599 --> 00:00:49.360
the great things I've heard is that the design of Positron has been greatly inspired by RStudio,

00:00:49.360 --> 00:00:55.360
so definitely something that I wanted to try. And those similarities between the two ideas

00:00:55.360 --> 00:01:01.439
made me think that the transition could be super cool, cruisy, maybe similar to having

00:01:01.439 --> 00:01:06.919
driven a good old car for many years and then switching to a different car, but not so different

00:01:06.919 --> 00:01:14.279
so that the challenge couldn't be great. Actually, what happened was a little bit more like a

00:01:14.279 --> 00:01:19.760
switch between an automatic car to a manual stick for the first time. A lot of the things

00:01:19.760 --> 00:01:25.680
that I used to do without thinking in RStudio suddenly started taking up a lot of effort.

00:01:25.680 --> 00:01:31.599
So certainly some frictions and pains. So it wasn't reflecting about those pains that

00:01:31.599 --> 00:01:35.879
I thought, well, the approach that I'm taking here is an approach that I've done many, many

00:01:35.879 --> 00:01:41.480
times before when I want to learn a new technology, I just dive in, push through the pain, and

00:01:41.480 --> 00:01:46.839
eventually you get used to it. But sometimes you cannot afford that. What if you are delivering

00:01:46.839 --> 00:01:52.720
a product next week or the week after and you just cannot afford slowing down? So here

00:01:52.720 --> 00:01:59.839
I would like to propose the idea of taking a different approach where we start the transition

00:01:59.839 --> 00:02:05.639
in RStudio itself by tweaking our workflow a little bit in a few specific ways that will

00:02:05.639 --> 00:02:12.759
help you get used to what's coming next. So here are my three tweaks, my three workflow

00:02:12.759 --> 00:02:18.679
tweaks that are working well for me, and maybe some of that works for you, too. First,

00:02:18.679 --> 00:02:25.679
use the commands palette. What is this? It's this text-based interface to running commands

00:02:26.160 --> 00:02:32.160
in RStudio. And this thing also exists in Positron and is the main way in which you

00:02:32.160 --> 00:02:38.639
are supposed to use the IDE. Why would you use this? Well, because that way you get used

00:02:38.679 --> 00:02:45.279
to running commands in a way that is not RStudio-specific. So instead of clicking on things, you just

00:02:45.279 --> 00:02:50.679
type a few keywords or a few keystrokes and you filter through the commands that are available

00:02:50.679 --> 00:02:55.759
to you and then hit enter and run them. And along the way, you will also discover the

00:02:55.759 --> 00:03:02.759
names of the commands that will be likely very similar in Positron 2. Tweak number two,

00:03:03.759 --> 00:03:10.759
use the terminal more. What I mean with this is basically talk to your computer in the

00:03:10.919 --> 00:03:17.279
most direct and efficient way possible. The terminal is both in Positron and RStudio,

00:03:17.279 --> 00:03:22.279
but it's also everywhere else. Even if you are using a remote server without a graphical

00:03:22.279 --> 00:03:29.279
user interface, you will still have a terminal. So you can still do a lot of stuff, stay productive,

00:03:29.679 --> 00:03:36.679
and not depend on RStudio or any IDE. And tweak number three, of course, use AI. Particularly,

00:03:40.000 --> 00:03:46.440
the AI tools that are agentic and they run from a CLI, from a command line interface,

00:03:46.440 --> 00:03:53.440
will allow you to get stuff done without an IDE, so you spend less time in the pain zone.

00:03:53.800 --> 00:03:59.240
In particular, I like Cloud Code and Gemini CLI precisely because of that. Wherever there

00:03:59.240 --> 00:04:05.080
is a terminal, there is this tool that will modify the source code on my behalf and not

00:04:05.080 --> 00:04:11.119
by being myself the one using the programming language, but indirectly through natural human

00:04:11.119 --> 00:04:18.119
language. So on top of being independent of an IDE, I'm gradually independent from programming

00:04:18.359 --> 00:04:25.359
language itself. And using AI effectively is in itself a huge challenge and something

00:04:25.640 --> 00:04:30.679
that certainly I'm still learning. But I'm now in the feeling that it's something worth

00:04:30.679 --> 00:04:36.119
trying because if you do that well, then you don't need to sit on the driver's seat. And

00:04:36.119 --> 00:04:40.359
instead, it feels like having a driver that if you give them the right directions, will

00:04:40.359 --> 00:04:47.359
take you wherever you want to go. And that I think is super cool. Thank you.

00:04:48.119 --> 00:04:49.119
Thank you.

00:04:49.119 --> 00:04:49.119


